==English==

===Adjective===
'''dyed-in-the-wool'''

# {{idiom}} Having had an occupation or viewpoint from very early on.
#: ''Smith was a dyed-in-the-wool typist and never really got used to writing on computers.''
The expression "'''dyed in the wool'''" refers to a state of steadfastness, usually in one's [[Politics|political]], [[Religion|religious]] or social beliefs. The expression comes from the fact that [[fabric]] can be [[dyed]] in a number of ways. The [[Weaving|woven]] fabric may be dyed after it is complete, or the threads may be dyed before they are woven. When a color is "dyed in the wool," the wool itself is dyed before being spun into [[thread]]s, so the colour is least likely to fade or change.

